One important application of the ideal gas law is to determine its molar mass and thereby            assist in its identification using the measured density of the gas. Review the            interactive below to see the derivation of the formula used to calculate the molar mass            of a gas from its density.
Press "NEXT" to advance slide show.
The molar mass of a gas can be determined given its density, temperature, and pressure            with the following equation:
\equire{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = \\frac{dRT}{P}
Where d = density, R = ideal gas law            constant, T = temperature, and P = pressure.
A gas was found to have a density of 0.0847 g/L at 17.0 C and a pressure of 760                torr. What is its molar mass? What is the gas?
\equire{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = \\frac{dRT}{P}
As before when using the ideal gas law constant, we need to ensure that the units in                the constant match the units used for the other variables and as before when using                the ideal gas law equation temperature must be in K. First we will convert the                pressure to units of atm. You will recall that 760 torr = 1 atm.
\equire{cancel} \equire{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = \\frac{(0.0847                    \\mathrm{g/}\\cancel{\\mathrm{L}})( 0.08206 \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}}\\                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{L}}\\ \\mathrm{mol^{-1}}\\ \\cancel{\\mathrm{K^{-1}}})(290                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{K}})}{1 \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}}}
\equire{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = 2.02 \\mathrm{g/mol}
The gas is hydrogen, H2.
This equation can also be used to determine the density of a known gas at a given            temperature and pressure.
Calculate the density of chlorine gas (Cl2) at 22 oC and 735 torr.
We can use the molar mass of a gas equation,
\equire{mathrsfs} \\mathscr{M} = \\frac{dRT}{P}
rearranging it to solve for density.
\equire{mathrsfs} d = \\frac{\\mathscr{M}P}{RT}
Because we know the identity of the gas, we can easily calculate its molar mass and                substitute it and the other given values (making the necessary conversions) into the                equation.
\equire{cancel} d = \\frac{(70.90 \\mathrm{g/}\\                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}})(0.967 \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}})}{ (0.08206                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}}\\ \\mathrm{L} \\cancel{\\mathrm{mol^{-1}}}\\                    \\cancel{\\mathrm{K^{-1}}})(295 \\cancel{\\mathrm{K}})} = 2.83                    \\mathrm{g/L}
